TOPIC: String Slicing

    - Reading more than one character at a time, multiple consecutive chars can be read using slice notation -

    slice notation -> my_string[start:end]
        + Creates new string whose value contains the characters of my_string from indices (start) to (end - 1)
        ---------------------------------
        my_string = "Armando"

        Name = my_string[0:3] -> "Arm"
        ---------------------------------
    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Notes:
        - Other sequence types like lists and tuples also support slice notation.

        - Last character of slice:
            + One location before the specified end.
            + Retrieve last character, an end index greater than the length of the string can be used.
            + Negative numbers can be used to specify an index relative to the end of the string.
                ---------------------------------
                my_string = "Armando"

                Name = my_string[0:-2] -> "Arman"
                ---------------------------------

        - Python interpreter creates a new string object for the slice.
            + Creating a slice of the string and then changing the value of that string does not
              change the value of the slice object.

        - Omitting a start index my_str[:3] yields chars from indices (0) to (end - 1)
        - Omitting a end index my_str[4:] yields chars from indices start to end of the string.

        - Slice stride:
            + Provides a 3rd argument known as stride.
            + Determines how much to increment the index after reading each element.
            + Stride defaults to 1 if not specified.
                ---------------------------------
                numbers = "0123456789"

                numbers[::] -> 0123456789
                numbers[::2] -> 02468
                numbers[1:9:3] -> 147
                ---------------------------------

        - Connecting slices:
            name = my_name[:1] + my_name[-1:] -> Ao

Common Slicing Operations:
 my_str = "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nasa/"

 Syntax	       | Result	                            | Description
 ..........................................................................................................................
 my_str[10:19] | wikipedia	                        | Returns the characters in indices 10-18.
 ..........................................................................................................................
 my_str[10:-5] | wikipedia.org/wiki/	            | Returns the characters in indices 10-28.
 ..........................................................................................................................
 my_str[8:]	   | n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nasa/	        | Returns all characters from index 8 until the end of the string.
 ..........................................................................................................................
 my_str[:23]   | http://en.wikipedia.org	        | Returns every character up to index 23, but not including my_str[23].
 ..........................................................................................................................
 my_str[:-1]   | http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nasa	| Returns all but the last character.

.......................................................................................................................
TOPIC: Advanced String Formatting

    - A program must display formatted output beyond the ability of basic print usage such as print(x) -

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Field Width: defines the minimum number of characters that must be inserted into the string.
        + format: print(f"{'Player Name': 16}{'Goals':8}")
            - String are left aligned by default; field width includes spaces after the string.
            - Numbers are right aligned by default; field width includes spaces before the number.

                    Player Name      Goals    Games Played     Goals Per Game
                    ------------------------------------------------------------
                    Sadio Mane         22          36               0.61
                    Mohamed Salah      22          38               0.58
                    Sergio Aguero      21          33               0.64
                    Jamie Vardy        18          34               0.53
                    Gabriel Jesus       7          29               0.24
                    ------------------------------------------------------------
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Aligning Character: determines how a value should be aligned within the width of the field.
        + set in a format specification by adding special characters before the field width integer:
            left-aligned: <
            right-aligned: >
            centered: ^
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
            Alignment Type          |           Code                      |           Output
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
            Left-Aligned            | f"{'Player Name':<16}{'Goals':<8}"  | Player_Name_____Goals__
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
            Right-Aligned           | f"{'Player Name':>16}{'Goals':>8}"  | _____Player_Name__Goals
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
              Centered              | f"{'Player Name':^16}{'Goals':^8}"  | __Player_Name___Goals___
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Fill: used to pad a replacement field when the inserted string is smaller than the field width.
        + The default filled character is an empty space " ".
        + Programmer may define a different fill character in a format specification by placing the
          different fill character before the alignment character.

                            Format specification | Value of score | Output
                            ----------------------------------------------
                            {score:}             |       9        | 9___
                            ----------------------------------------------
                            {score:4}            |       9        | ___9
                            ----------------------------------------------
                            {score:0>4}          |       9        | 0009
                            ----------------------------------------------
                            {score:0>4}          |       18       | 0018
                            ----------------------------------------------
                            {score:0^4}          |       18       | 0180
                            ----------------------------------------------
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Floating-point precision: indicates how many digits should be included in the output.
        + format: f"1.725:.1f}" -> 1.7
        + If the specified precision is greater than the number of digits available, trailing 0s are
          appended.
        + If the specified precision is less than the existing precision in the given number, then
          the number is rounded.
