TOPIC: String Methods

    - String objects have many useful methods to do things like: -
        + replacing characters
        + converting to lowercase
        + capitalizing the first character
        + more!
    - Strings are immutable: once created strings can not be changed.
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Finding and Replacing
        + to update a string variable, a new string object must be created and bound to the variable name,
          replacing the old object.
        + the replace string method provides a simple way to create a new string by replacing all occurrences
          of a substring with a new substring.

        replace(old, new)
          + returns a copy of the string with all occurrences of the substring (old)
              by the new string (new).

        replace(old, new, count)
          + same as above, except replace(old, new, count) only replaces the first count occurrences of old.

        phrase = "My name is Armando"

        phrase = phrase.replace("Armando", "Lena")

        Output: My name is Lena
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Finding position of character / substring

        find(x) -
            returns the index of the first occurrence of item x in the string, otherwise, find(x) returns -1
                + x may be a string variable or string literal.

            my_name = "Armando" |       my_name.find('A') returns 0
                                |       my_name.find('Arm') returns 0
            my_name = "ArmandoArm" |    my_name.find('Arm') returns 0, first occurrence only!

        find(x, start) -
            same as find(x) but begins search at index start.

            my_name = "Armando" |       my_name.find("a", 2) returns 3

        find(x, start, end) -
            same as find(x, start) but stops search at index (end - 1)

            my_name = "ArmandoLena" |   my_name.find("a", 4, len(my_name) - 1) returns 11

        rfind(x) -
            same as find(x) but searches the string in reverse, returning the last occurrence of the string.

        count(x) -
            returns the number of times x occurs in the string.

    NOTE:
        - find(x) and rfind(x) are useful only for cases where programmer needs to know the exact location
          of the character or substring in the string.

        - (in membership) operator should be used to check if a character or substring is contained in the string.

            if "batman" is superhero_name:
               # statements to execute if superhero_name contains "batman" in any position.
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Comparing Strings

            Example	            |    Expression result	 |                           Why?
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    "Hello" == "Hello"	        |          True	         |  The strings are exactly identical values
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    "Hello" == "Hello!"	        |          False	     |  The left hand string does not end with "!".
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    "Yankee Sierra" > "Amy Wise"|	       True	         |  The first character of the left side "Y" is "greater than"
                                |                        |  (in ASCII value) the first character of the right side "A".
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    "Yankee Sierra"             |	       False	     |  The characters of both sides match until the second word.
             >                  |                        | The first character of the second word on the left "S" is not
    "Yankee Zulu"               |                        | "greater than" (in ASCII value) the first character on the right side "Z".
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    "seph" in "Joseph"      	|           True	     | The substring "seph" can be found starting at the 3rd position of "Joseph".
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    "jo" in "Joseph"	        |           False	     | "jo" (with a lowercase "j") is not in "Joseph" (with an uppercase "J").

    Note:
        + If one string is shorter than the other when comparing less than or equal, the shorter string is
          considered less than the longer string.

    Membership operators (in, not in)
        + provide a simple method for detecting whether a specific substring exists in the string.
            - the argument to the right of the operator is examined for the existence of the argument on the left.

    Identity operators (is, is not)
        + determine whether the two arguments are bound to the same object.
            - common error is to use identity operator in place of an equality operator: name is "Armando Sarza"

    OTHER methods to check a string value that returns TRUE or FALSE Boolean value:
        -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        isalnum()       | True if all characters in the string are lowercase or uppercase, or numbers 0-9
        -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        isdigit()       | True if all characters are the numbers 0-9
        -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        islower()       | True if all cased characters are lowercase letters
        -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        isupper()       | True if all cased characters are uppercase letters
        -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        isspace()       | True if all characters are whitespace
        -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        startswith(x)   | True if the string starts with x
        -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        endswith(x)     | True if the string ends with x

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Creating new strings from a string

    - Programmer often transform two strings into similar formats to perform a comparison. -
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    capitalize()    | returns a copy of the string with the first char capitalized and the rest lowercased.
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    lower()         | returns a copy of the string with all characters lowercased.
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    upper()         | returns a copy of the string with all characters uppercased.
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    strip()         | returns a copy of the string with leading and trailing whitespace removed.
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    title()         | returns a copy of the string as a title, with first letters of words capitalized.
