TOPIC: Splitting and Joining Strings
    Purpose: breaking a large string down into the comprising substrings.
-----------------
split() method -
-----------------
    + splits a string into a LIST of tokens.
        - each token is a substring that forms a part of a larger string.
        - separator: is a character chosen by programmer that indicates where to split the string into tokens.
            ex. "My name is Armando".split() -> ["My", "name", "is", "Armando"]
                "My, name, is, Lena".split(",") -> ["My", "name", "is", "Lena"]
                my_list = input().split()
    + if the split string starts or ends with the separator, or if two consecutive separator exists, then
      the resulting list will contain an empty string for each such occurrence.
    + if the separator is omitted from split(), thus splitting the string wherever whitespace occurs,
      then no empty strings are generated.
    + Additional: inserting into the list created
        list_created.insert(index, "word")

-----------------
join() method -
-----------------
    + performs the inverse operation of split() by joining a list of strings together to create a single string.
        ex. user_name = ["My", "name", "is", "Armando"] |   Output:
            separator = "+"                             |       My+name+is+Armando
            name = separator.join(user_name)            |
            --------------------------------------------
        ex. intro_message = "+".join(user_name)
    + Useful application of the join() method is to build a new string without separators.
    + join() vs loops:
        - join() is much simpler approach that uses less code and is easier to read.











